In late 2008, $10 million (part of the original $75 million promised by Governor Pataki) was released by Governor Paterson to begin the acquisition of the land necessary for the project. The first piece of land, a {{convert|0.5|acre|ha|adj=on}} parking lot, was bought in July 2009 from [[Greyhound Lines, Inc.]] at a cost of $469,673.<ref name=land1>{{Cite news|title=Deal Signals Start of Acquisition |last=Carleo-Evangelist |first=Jordan |publisher=Hearst Newspapers |work=Times Union (Albany) |date=2009-08-01 |accessdate=2010-09-02 |page=B4 |url=http://albarchive.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=8431148}}</ref> In August 2009, the Albany County Legislature approved the sale of nine vacant county-owned lots<U+2014>totaling {{convert|0.39|acre|ha}}<U+2014>to the ACCA at a cost of $453,000.<ref name=land2>{{Cite news|title=Center Land Buys Grow |first=Jordan |last=Carleo-Evangelist |publisher=Hearst Newspapers |work=Times Union (Albany) |accessdate=2010-09-02 |date=2009-08-29 |page=B8 |url=http://albarchive.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=8585004}}</ref> In February 2010, the ACCA bought about {{convert|0.5|acre|ha}} of land, which brought its total to about {{convert|1.5|acre|ha}}.<ref name=land3/> In August 2010 it purchased about {{convert|3|acre|ha}} of land at a cost of $5.9 million. After this sale, the ACCA had acquired about 75% of the land necessary for the project.<ref name=aug>{{Cite news|title=Convention center pieces fall into place |first=Jordan |last=Carleo-Evangelist |publisher=Hearst Newspapers |work=Times Union (Albany) |date=2010-08-27 |page= |accessdate=2010-08-29 |url=http://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Convention-center-pieces-fall-into-place-634265.php| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100918074320/http://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Convention-center-pieces-fall-into-place-634265.php| archivedate= 18 September 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

In November 2009, the ACCA revealed its design, developed by [[HNTB]]. A formal price was also released: $220 million. The ACCA was able to drop from its earlier $400 million estimate by turning hotel and parking garage development over to private developers. This brought the cost estimate down to between $225 million and $240 million. After considering the cost of goods and commodities during the economic recession, the estimate dropped again to $220 million.<ref name=design/>

Because the project was not [[Shovel ready|shovel-ready]] at the time, the ACC was not eligible for [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|stimulus funds]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=No Money in Stimulus Package for Convention Center |first=Michael |last=DeMasi |publisher=The Business Review (Albany) |work=American City Business Journals, Inc |date=2009-01-30 |accessdate=2010-08-30 |url=http://albany.bizjournals.com/albany/stories/2009/01/26/daily55.html}}</ref>
{{-}}

==Description==
[[File:Albany Convention Center 2.jpg|thumb|250px|Bird's eye view of the proposed Albany Convention Center {{as of|lc=y|2009|11}}; Broadway is shown at bottom-left, Hudson Avenue is along right side.]]
The ACC will be located along Broadway between the [[South Mall Arterial]] and Hudson Avenue. The current site consists mostly of surface-level parking lots.<ref name=land3>{{Cite news|title=Convention Center Land Buys Continue |last=Churchill |first=Chris |publisher=Hearst Newspapers |work=Times Union (Albany) |date=2010-02-25 |page=C1 |accessdate=2010-08-30 |url=http://albarchive.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=9692907}}</ref> The design will consist mainly of a brick and glass structure. The meeting area would comprise an exhibition hall, two ballrooms and other various meeting spaces totaling about {{convert|300000|sqft|m2}}.<ref name=design/>

In early 2008, it was announced that the site would include a 400-room Sheraton Hotel, to be run by Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide Inc., of [[White Plains, New York|White Plains]]; a {{convert|300000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} convention center, to be operated by SMG Management<U+2014>the company that operates the Times Union Center<U+2014>and an 1,100-car parking garage. A bridge will also connect the convention center to the Times Union Center.<ref name=jan2008/> The back of the center will be pushed up against the South Mall Arterial, with loading docks on that side. A plaza will be built near the center of the complex, facing Broadway. The design will allow for future expansion of the convention space, if needed.<ref name=design>{{Cite news|title=Designs on Downtown Albany's Future |last=Churchill |first=Chris |publisher=Hearst Newspapers |work=Times Union (Albany) |date=2009-11-20 |accessdate=2010-09-02 |page=A1 |url=http://albarchive.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=9044605}}</ref>

Within the site boundary is the [[Van Ostrande-Radliff House]], one of the oldest houses in the [[Capital District]], which is also believed to be the oldest building in the city of Albany.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Albany Preservation Report | page = 7 | publisher = Historic Albany Foundation | date = Spring 2007 |format=PDF | accessdate = 2010-09-04 | url = http://www.historic-albany.org/HAF%20SP07%20newsletter%20for%20web.pdf}}</ref> The house was built by Johannes van Ostrande around 1728 and is a rare example of Dutch architecture from its time. Owner Brian Parker came into agreement with the ACCA that the building would be saved, possibly making use of it as a visitor's center.<ref>{{Cite news|title=This Old House Under Our Noses |last=Grondahl |first=Paul |publisher=Hearst Newspapers |work=Times Union (Albany) |date=2008-12-23 |accessdate=2010-09-02 |page=D1 |url=http://albarchive.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=7306654}}</ref>

==Controversy==
The Albany Convention Center has seen significant opposition from its inception. Opposing viewpoints offer a range of alternative plans. Some state that Albany doesn't need a convention center at all, some suggest the ACCA consider expanding current convention facilities and others have proposed moving the project to other areas of the city, such as the [[University Heights, Albany, New York|University Heights]] neighborhood, the [[College of Nanoscale Science and Engineering]] campus, or the [[W. Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus|Harriman State Office Campus]].<ref name=feb>{{Cite news|title=Forget About an Albany Convention Center |first=Paul |last=Bray |publisher=Hearst Newspapers |work=Times Union (Albany) |page=B2 |date=2010-02-14 |accessdate=2010-08-29 |url=http://albarchive.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=9502749}}</ref> It has also been suggested that since the ACCA has already accumulated some funds (though not enough to complete the current plans), it should instead invest the capital in buying up vacant buildings and renovating them as a stimulus for the downtown economy. Opponents question the cost of the project, especially during such difficult fiscal times.<ref name=land3/>

Even considering the economic crisis, the Albany area has seen a general shortage of construction workers. The $4.2 billion [[GlobalFoundries]] chip plant that was begun in nearby Malta in 2008 already strained the labor market and some worry that building the ACC will just exacerbate the problem.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Build It and There May Be a Labor Shortage |last=Churchill |first=Chris |publisher=Hearst Newspapers |work=Times Union (Albany) |date=2009-08-17 |accessdate=2010-09-02 |page=A1 |url=http://albarchive.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=8505135}}</ref>

